saging seeking to "rat-proof" their beliefs along with their houses. The transformation of houses, villages, and peoples was documented in hundreds of photographs and broadcast to overseas audiences as evidence of the "ethical" nature of colonial rule, proving so effective as propaganda that the rebuilding continued even as better alternatives, such as inoculation, became available. By systematically reshaping the built environment, the Dutch plague response dramatically expanded colonial oversight and influence in rural Java.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aPlaguezIndonesiazJavaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthzIndonesiazJavaxHistoryy20th century. 4aArchitecture & Preservation. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPublic Health. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh  acolonial medicine and colonial photography, home improvement in Java, Dutch colonial period, bamboo houses and plague control, Dutch colonial health policy, rat-flea-man transmission theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176684840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501766848423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501766848/original  a978-3-11-075182-6  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK